\end{align*}We notice that the left-hand side is the original polynomial multiplied out, so the right-hand side is the expanded form of our polynomial.  From here, it is straightforward to see that the leading term on the right-hand side is the term of highest degree.  That term occurs when each variable is raised to the highest possible power, i.e., $$(a-b)(a-c)(b-c)\cdot x^2.$$So, since this term occurs with degree 2, the degree of the polynomial is $\boxed{2}.$ The answer is: 2.

